436 The shortness of the sea passage—the shortness of the distance between the island and the mainland—has given currency, has given support to the fictions of common repert. The distance of Corsica from the mainland is about fifty-five miles. Strabo 5, 2, 7 says that it can be seen from the shore of Populonia; but from this statement Itasius Lemniacus dissents. The story referred to is that a Ligurian woman named Corsa, who was servant oi a herdsman, having noticed that one of their cattle used to swim across the sea, and return much fatter and in better condition, conjectured that there must be a fertile island at no great distance. Search was consequently made, and Corsica discovered.
